{"userName": "George Station", "sentiment_emotions": [], "hashtags": [], "userID": "103316555196135859733", "content": "+ Justin Schwamm re: your colleagues&#39; version, that not doing worksheets [or other factory equivalent] may be connected to a bad grade\u2014that remains a core tenet of higher ed, right up through master&#39;s level. There is a core amount of &quot;rote&quot; at baseline that never totally goes away in our system. Connectivism challenges that, where you can get away with it. You can also flip the message (doing the core rote stuff at barely satisfactory level might earn [or &quot;earn&quot; if you prefer] a C, which may sound like a GOOD DEAL for some people) but it is still a factory message. You want to go somewhere else with it...so back over to you...?", "sentiment_score": 0.05555555555555555, "cleanContent": "+ Justin Schwamm re: your colleagues' version, that not doing worksheets [or other factory equivalent] may be connected to a bad grade\u2014that remains a core tenet of higher ed, right up through master's level. There is a core amount of \"rote\" at baseline that never totally goes away in our system. Connectivism challenges that, where you can get away with it. {"userName": "Brendan Storming", "sentiment_emotions": [], "hashtags": [], "userID": "105908654959068260105", "content": "I think that teachers sharing their &quot;teaching-journey story&quot; can be a big step toward changing how things work. \u00a0When people have a good sense of where they&#39;ve come from, when they&#39;ve processed their backstory and it&#39;s part of the discussion, I think it can open the door to saying &quot;what next in the journey,&quot; in a way that can be hard when people are thinking in terms of &quot;always&quot; and &quot;this is how school works&quot; and &quot;this is how I do things.&quot; Likewise, with students... their learning journey. When people have a good sense of where they've come from, when they've processed their backstory and it's part of the discussion, I think it can open the door to saying \"what next in the journey,\" in a way that can be hard when people are thinking in terms of \"always\" and \"this is how school works\" and \"this is how I do things.\" Likewise, with students... their learning journey. One thing that inhibits all this is the fact that it's hard to conceive of life as a journey, when not much ever seems to change, and there's no particular destination. For some people, there is a destination, or at least several options, or a rough sense of one. But, many others don't have such a clear-cut sense of what could be. And that lack of a vision for the future, combined with the day-in and day-out drudgery that school is for many students (and teachers, and parents), makes it hard to conceptualize a journey in the sense of what a very good story or life quest would offer. (This links back to \"Steps on a Journey, I,\" https://plus.google.com/102340336817210055995/posts/gaT7t4YFn3R -- and that whole week's discussions.) \"The 20th-century mindset reserves journeys and quests for Other People \u2013 especially fictional ones with movies, books, and marketing tie-ins \u2013 but when you stop and think about it, we journey and quest every day, even when our days seem humdrum and routine. To pretend otherwise is to deny something essential about our humanity ... and yet, when you stop and think about it, how often have you pretended you weren't doing (or being) Anything Special? \" It's one thing to conceptualize one's self, activities, and day-to-day goals as \"journeys or quests,\" but it's another thing to really have a good inner model of being on a journey that spans long periods of one's life. That's part of what many people are missing in their self-schema. A realization of key plot points earlier on... and processing them into a meaningful sequence, can do a lot not only for self-awareness, but for having a grounding in understanding that other people have different journeys. A simple example of that is how people's minds work differently, and people have different things that will motivate and inspire them. Of course, people realize this on a basic level, but it doesn't get translated into classroom discussions very often. {"userName": "Brendan Storming", "sentiment_emotions": [], "hashtags": [], "userID": "105908654959068260105", "content": "+ Justin Schwamm \u00a0Moving from reaction to response is an important step. \u00a0But that opens up a range of further questions. \u00a0Dispensing with yelling and labeling is good... and setting expectations and expressing disappointment in a calm, controlled manner models a better way to respond than having a meltdown of some kind. But, there are layers more to deal with. \u00a0In the classroom management video I watched the other day -- an entire class period -- I saw a calm, controlled, if rather strange, approach to total classroom control. \u00a0And, I see why it works. \u00a0The thread I posted that into is a rich source of material for discussion:\u00a0 https://plus.google.com/114911896336915116400/posts/N3vFWuc8yLd In short, there certainly are ways to exert control in a totally calm manner. \u00a0Expressing being appalled, and disappointed, or even letting the students own their failures as something that&#39;s their choice and their loss, are all far better than faculty (or parent) meltdowns. But, I think the pattern is still one of bringing about compliance . \u00a0It&#39;s a much healthier form of compliance, but it&#39;s still per-task compliance. Even when students have a choice in the assignment, and a chance to express feedback about it. \u00a0Even when the assignments are carefully designed to match the learners&#39; cognitive styles and preferences. \u00a0Even when the activity results in a joyful experience . \u00a0Even when the activity results in measurable, genuine learning . \u00a0Even when all of Bloom&#39;s taxonomy levels are met. And this is where the truly challenging part of transforming education comes into play. I think there&#39;s a place for task compliance , and that learners can benefit from them. \u00a0In fact, this is how many games operate. \u00a0And, of course, life requires the completion of tasks. \u00a0Even creative professions require what Seth Godin calls shipping. Done well, eliciting task compliance in a reflective, responsive, reckoned manner is far better than the hostile, toxic, emotionally dysfunctional brew of people having meltdowns , modeling adult life as a condition of suffering , and sobbing and yelling on a regular basis. \u00a0And it&#39;s better than issuing threats , calling parents , and having people report to Higher Powers for handling by another level in the &quot;comply or defy&quot; chain. But, back to that pattern that&#39;s still a mystery. \u00a0There&#39;s something about the way factory-model schools are structured, even when run perfectly (including embracing imperfection , having a healthy dose of humor, and providing a joyful experience for all) that&#39;s out of place in the 21st century world... and that will be even more so as the century progresses. In short, school can still be a cave. \u00a0(&quot;School and the Allegory of the Cave &quot;,\u00a0 http://forums.school-survival.net/showthread.php?tid=29550 ) And... not just school... but the unhappy, disengaging work situations that many people end up in... or the lack of work that can be even worse. \u00a0Even more so in a world that is more of a network of networks than a top-down world of &quot;everything&#39;s under control.&quot; Finding solutions to that problem is going to require a different kind of interaction between learners and educators -- and it&#39;s beyond the scope of this comment. \u00a0But, it&#39;s something to think about... find ways to discuss in the form of broader learning conversations.", "sentiment_score": 0.14642524916943522, "cleanContent": "+ Justin Schwamm Moving from reaction to response is an important step. But that opens up a range of further questions. Dispensing with yelling and labeling is good... and setting expectations and expressing disappointment in a calm, controlled manner models a better way to respond than having a meltdown of some kind. But, there are layers more to deal with. In the classroom management video I watched the other day -- an entire class period -- I saw a calm, controlled, if rather strange, approach to total classroom control. And, I see why it works. The thread I posted that into is a rich source of material for discussion: https://plus.google.com/114911896336915116400/posts/N3vFWuc8yLd In short, there certainly are ways to exert control in a totally calm manner. Expressing being appalled, and disappointed, or even letting the students own their failures as something that's their choice and their loss, are all far better than faculty (or parent) meltdowns. But, I think the pattern is still one of bringing about compliance . It's a much healthier form of compliance, but it's still per-task compliance. Even when students have a choice in the assignment, and a chance to express feedback about it. Even when the assignments are carefully designed to match the learners' cognitive styles and preferences. Even when the activity results in a joyful experience . Even when the activity results in measurable, genuine learning . Even when all of Bloom's taxonomy levels are met. And this is where the truly challenging part of transforming education comes into play. I think there's a place for task compliance , and that learners can benefit from them. In fact, this is how many games operate. And, of course, life requires the completion of tasks. Even creative professions require what Seth Godin calls shipping. Done well, eliciting task compliance in a reflective, responsive, reckoned manner is far better than the hostile, toxic, emotionally dysfunctional brew of people having meltdowns , modeling adult life as a condition of suffering , and sobbing and yelling on a regular basis. And it's better than issuing threats , calling parents , and having people report to Higher Powers for handling by another level in the \"comply or defy\" chain. But, back to that pattern that's still a mystery. There's something about the way factory-model schools are structured, even when run perfectly (including embracing imperfection , having a healthy dose of humor, and providing a joyful experience for all) that's out of place in the 21st century world... and that will be even more so as the century progresses. In short, school can still be a cave. (\"School and the Allegory of the Cave \", ) And... not just school... but the unhappy, disengaging work situations that many people end up in... or the lack of work that can be even worse. Even more so in a world that is more of a network of networks than a top-down world of \"everything's under control.\" Finding solutions to that problem is going to require a different kind of interaction between learners and educators -- and it's beyond the scope of this comment. But, it's something to think about... find ways to discuss in the form of broader learning conversations.", "postID": "z12rdfhowknxhbn4e04cij3gnqnohjoix0w.1381321802228466"}

{"userName": "Debbie Pribele", "sentiment_emotions": [], "hashtags": [], "userID": "113508712170563926845", "content": "we used the terms react/respond all the time in our anger management programs. React, more of a reflex and respond, a thought-out choice.\u00a0 I have already forwarded your definitions to my colleague that I used to work with.\u00a0 I am reminded of a moment with my grandson yesterday. He was putting together a number puzzle and at one point he stopped and was just staring at the puzzle. I say &quot;just&quot; but of course it wasn&#39;t &quot;just&quot;. My first &quot;reaction&quot; thought was to jump-start the puzzle-making again by asking him, &quot;what comes next&quot; or something like that. But my &quot;response&quot; thought was to just wait. I don&#39;t know what was going on in his mind. He might have been processing some new understanding about numbers or puzzles. Perhaps he was in the middle of an ah-ha moment.\u00a0 When he was done doing whatever he was doing he continued with the puzzle. When he is older and can communicate better I would follow such a moment with some questions to find out what he was thinking about but because he is only 2, I have to leave the question unanswered.\u00a0 Sometimes the best response is no response - and definitely a checked reaction!", "sentiment_score": 0.22235454545454547, "cleanContent": "we used the terms react/respond all the time in our anger management programs. React, more of a reflex and respond, a thought-out choice. I have already forwarded your definitions to my colleague that I used to work with. I am reminded of a moment with my grandson yesterday. He was putting together a number puzzle and at one point he stopped and was just staring at the puzzle. I say \"just\" but of course it wasn't \"just\". My first \"reaction\" thought was to jump-start the puzzle-making again by asking him, \"what comes next\" or something like that. But my \"response\" thought was to just wait. I don't know what was going on in his mind. He might have been processing some new understanding about numbers or puzzles. Perhaps he was in the middle of an ah-ha moment. When he was done doing whatever he was doing he continued with the puzzle. When he is older and can communicate better I would follow such a moment with some questions to find out what he was thinking about but because he is only 2, I have to leave the question unanswered. Sometimes the best response is no response - and definitely a checked reaction!", "postID": "z12hy1jilquyif2h504cij3gnqnohjoix0w.1381232660339082"}
{"userName": "Mark Poole", "sentiment_emotions": [], "hashtags": [], "userID": "102169795540290746973", "content": "+ Justin Schwamm \u00a0 Reacting and Responding directly connects to your blog post yesterday on Knowing What, \u00a0Knowing Why, and Knowing When . Reactions happen when individuals or groups of people are impacted by the actions of other individuals or systematic processes imposed on individuals or groups of people. In the times which we live, many actions or processes do not pass the test of What, Why, and When . In a perfect world it would be possible to have everyone responding to these situations but that world does not exist. Your teaching colleague&#39;s choice to retire sooner rather than later will have an impact on many who come in contact with her. She made a critical choice at the beginning of a school year that if tested against Knowing When and then a subsequent different choice had been made for announcing when she would retire, might have produced a better set of responses compared to the constant set of reactions her choice is producing. In a recent episode of the Good Life Project + Jonathan Fields \u00a0\u00a0tossed out an even better set of mechanics that if understood and used will produce responses instead of reactions. His guest was talking about her choices and how important why is. This guest made the point that she did not treat questions of why like checkbox answers. It was at this point that Fields made a comment which can be life transforming when understood. http://goo.gl/1TRMon When we have choices these choices are all about our desires. As we consider a desire it\u2019s important to ask why . Fields points out that if we continue to push down on questions of why it will eventually get emotional. In the cases of many of our desires, when we arrive at answers for why , many of our desires will melt away. In these instances we will learn that our desires are matters of emotion and not physical needs that are often represented as physical desires. In cases where we come up with answers for why, we are signaled to move forward where the next obvious question to answer is how . Drilling down on how will answer questions of time, resources, and both of these in a format we are all familiar with, money. With why and how questions addressed we will almost always be able to attain our choices/desires. This process of answering the why and how of our desires has been short circuited by many different daily tasks and also by how we are spending so much time reacting to things we encounter. Picture cat chasing its tail. With desires that are in reality unmet emotional needs , and missing answers for why and how , we are filling these desires unmet needs in such a way that over time these desires become expectations . As individuals we use our money and time filling physical desires and dealing with the emotional fallout that comes from reacting to our poor choices. When individuals act as groups we can see how institutional thinking also follows this same malformed thinking path. As a society we have a desire to be happy and successful . Without proper answers for why and how we wind up with an education system that has the stated expectation No Child Left Behind . I think it is safe to say that filling unmet emotional needs posing as desires, without first addressing Why and How , will more often than not produce reactions and not Responses .", "sentiment_score": 0.15553923205342238, "cleanContent": "+ Justin Schwamm Reacting and Responding directly connects to your blog post yesterday on Knowing What, Knowing Why, and Knowing When . Reactions happen when individuals or groups of people are impacted by the actions of other individuals or systematic processes imposed on individuals or groups of people. In the times which we live, many actions or processes do not pass the test of What, Why, and When . In a perfect world it would be possible to have everyone responding to these situations but that world does not exist. Your teaching colleague's choice to retire sooner rather than later will have an impact on many who come in contact with her. She made a critical choice at the beginning of a school year that if tested against Knowing When and then a subsequent different choice had been made for announcing when she would retire, might have produced a better set of responses compared to the constant set of reactions her choice is producing. In a recent episode of the Good Life Project + Jonathan Fields tossed out an even better set of mechanics that if understood and used will produce responses instead of reactions. His guest was talking about her choices and how important why is. This guest made the point that she did not treat questions of why like checkbox answers. It was at this point that Fields made a comment which can be life transforming when understood. When we have choices these choices are all about our desires. As we consider a desire it\u2019s important to ask why . Fields points out that if we continue to push down on questions of why it will eventually get emotional. In the cases of many of our desires, when we arrive at answers for why , many of our desires will melt away. In these instances we will learn that our desires are matters of emotion and not physical needs that are often represented as physical desires. In cases where we come up with answers for why, we are signaled to move forward where the next obvious question to answer is how . Drilling down on how will answer questions of time, resources, and both of these in a format we are all familiar with, money. With why and how questions addressed we will almost always be able to attain our choices/desires. This process of answering the why and how of our desires has been short circuited by many different daily tasks and also by how we are spending so much time reacting to things we encounter. Picture cat chasing its tail. With desires that are in reality unmet emotional needs , and missing answers for why and how , we are filling these desires unmet needs in such a way that over time these desires become expectations . As individuals we use our money and time filling physical desires and dealing with the emotional fallout that comes from reacting to our poor choices. When individuals act as groups we can see how institutional thinking also follows this same malformed thinking path. As a society we have a desire to be happy and successful . Without proper answers for why and how we wind up with an education system that has the stated expectation No Child Left Behind . I think it is safe to say that filling unmet emotional needs posing as desires, without first addressing Why and How , will more often than not produce reactions and not Responses .", "postID": "z12hy1jilquyif2h504cij3gnqnohjoix0w.1381241439310504"}

There are many sides of that process. But, what gives rise to who a person becomes at various points along the journey? How much is it directed by one's temperament, one's genetic programming, one's culture, one's random situations, one's parents and schools, the people one happens to be around... the media one consumes, and all that? And, how much is a matter of choice and effort on the part of the individual? Of course, it's an interplay between those things... an interplay guided in part by people's beliefs, mindset, and levels of awareness. But, what does one do, when the educational structures one is confronted with seem to block meaningful development of self? What does one do, when one doesn't connect with people who encourage and support \"becoming who you are?\" Unfortunately, many elders seem to have the belief, and send the message, \"I'm not able to be who I am, so neither will you.\" That's a dark way to think about it... but it's too often what plays out. Certainly, it's useful to have some tension between \"being who one is\" and \"moving toward one's potential,\" but the key question is, where does that come from? Who defines it? Is the \"end goal\" to learn to comply with a factory routine, and follow the rules, or to understand and empathize with actual people's needs, and be able to creatively take steps to help them achieve their goals? This whole question of identity is a big discussion, indeed. And it's one that deserves more attention. That question might have a simple answer in the moment, but it's more complicated to think about in terms of how to teach and mentor in significant ways. What kinds of learning and growth can be facilitated, as part of that process of support? It's often when people are going through something major, that they're most open to learning and growing. Without some kind of spark, at least, it can be hard to even initiate a learning experience. I've found that to be the case for me, and quite a few others as well. I think one key to changing things is to explore the idea, \"if we put our needs first\" ... Is it really a problem of \"our needs first,\" in a world with too many needs to handle? Or, is it an opportunity to identify unrecognized needs, and look for ways to meet more of them with less effort? + Mark Poole talks about this idea through the framework of \"lean thinking,\" eliminating wasted effort. I like the language of \"Theory of Constraints,\" which talks about finding bottlenecks and looking for weak links that are limiting performance. Is there really not enough time? Or is there a way to find the time? Are people busy attending to their own needs, or are they not attending to any needs, because they aren't effectively noticing them... or because they don't know what to do? That's a good bridge to a possible solution... professional development books like the one + Justin Schwamm mentioned today. But already, there's a risk: even if a big wall of text book or article has potential value, will potential learners look for that value, or see it as \"another thing to do\" , \"touchy-feely\" (or the opposite, too theoretical), or \"unrealistic\" ? And that goes back to the basic problem of teaching, or mentoring, beyond facilitating content memorization and task compliance. As I try to design a course, I wonder... how to get anyone to pay attention... when it's not something they \"have to do,\" or in a format they've \"always\" used, or in response to an immediate need. That's one reason recognizing and discovering needs (want wants) is so important in designing better learning environments. But how to bring about the Big Convergence of teachers & learners in a lifelong learning community -- or, per + don arnoldy awhile back, principled integration into a professional (joyful?) community-of-practice -- is the Big Enchilada. As a 'not-a-professional' educator, I obviously still struggle with how to even talk about all this in this circle. But I know it has something to do with expert scaffolding and cocreation, -- concepts I picked up from you folks -- and looks something like this: Here's what we know. Take it, creatively apply your gifts, and make it your own. Then share it with others as a resource and let them do the same. What would happen if 'curriculum' was some sort of digital resource instead of a finished publication (print or digital), and learners were to cocreate a version for themselves, within a principled, peer-reviewed framework? That's the only way I know of where marginalized indigenous language communities were truly able to take ownership of life-crucial information. And many have learned the hard way that memorizing 'foreign' concepts can be deadly in that case. But I honestly have no idea if/how that approach would work for you folks and your learning communities in the 'more-developed' world. I do know that it's not been met with open arms by the education establishment or publishing industry over the years, and it's increasingly at risk through lack of technical support. Programmers generally have the expectation of high pay, and those are two powerful industries. I like the idea of a school-wide seminar, but I wonder how a single event might fit into the broader discussion. \u00a0When people are having creativity and initiative &quot;beaten out of them,&quot; and are dealing with a pedagogy of siloed subjects, a single clip is needs to be followed up with some kind of supporting discussion. \u00a0Asking students (and teachers) to submit and discuss questions in some online space could be one way to do that. Providing steps to take for further conversations could be another. \u00a0One of the drawbacks of the edu-MOOCs I&#39;ve seen is that they&#39;re time-limited, obscure and hard to find, in the grand scheme of things, and don&#39;t necessarily draw participants into the most important conversations. \u00a0Biggest of all, they tend not to really be designed around traditional &quot;student&quot; participation. But, they&#39;re a step, like that also-obscure Hacking Education conference, toward the vision of learners providing input to occur in further iterations. \u00a0_&quot;I wonder what small, but vital part we can play in that process, today&quot;_ indeed!", "sentiment_score": 0.07403846153846154, "cleanContent": "+ Justin Schwamm Are B and O familiar with Ken Robinson's other talks, and the vast set of parallel conversations that people have been having? In terms of editing together a short clip, I'd suggest looking at his Lincoln quote in his follow-up talk about \"disenthrall ourselves,\" and definitely Changing Education Paradigms. There's also the question of what the solution is. One approach is connected learning , or connectivism, which George Siemens wrote about in 2004, -- that article could be a good source of questions. This summary outline of the 2009 Hacking Education discussion, which Ken Robinson attended, gets at the changes many people agree are coming to education, including the learner making their own decisions, learners acting as teachers, and so on: (Audio and text transcripts... which I just came across: https://publicusv.wiki.zoho.com/Hacking-Education-Discussion.html?pid=169095000000011003 ) One quote from Sir Ken there, speaking about his first TED talk, \"And this video has been downloaded now 4 million times, which is great, from some points of view. But my son recently showed me a video, that's also on YouTube, of two kittens that seem to be having a conversation. It takes 90 seconds, and that's been downloaded 18 million times.\" And, years later, and two TED talks later, many students are still not part of that conversation. Many students continue to be told, by their Relevant Parental Powers that grades and school compliance are what matters, while even Ms. X wants to give her students some ownership of their learning. This is quite a problem to disentangle! One of Sir Ken's big themes is not only how schools kill creativity, but how they fail to support people in discovering and developing their natural talents and passions. Many people assume college is the place whether that happens -- and it is for some -- but many others find that not to be the case, as he references in Changing Education Paradigms. So, why all those years of school? How might they be done differently? \"...perhaps I have an important role to play in this place at this time during the transition.\" I agree. It's a role that's much easier to play when students are driving the questions, and other teachers are looking for the joy-and-wonder side of education. There's still the question of what exactly to do, when it comes to the larger conversations. I like the idea of a school-wide seminar, but I wonder how a single event might fit into the broader discussion. When people are having creativity and initiative \"beaten out of them,\" and are dealing with a pedagogy of siloed subjects, a single clip is needs to be followed up with some kind of supporting discussion. Asking students (and teachers) to submit and discuss questions in some online space could be one way to do that. Providing steps to take for further conversations could be another. One of the drawbacks of the edu-MOOCs I've seen is that they're time-limited, obscure and hard to find, in the grand scheme of things, and don't necessarily draw participants into the most important conversations. Biggest of all, they tend not to really be designed around traditional \"student\" participation. But, they're a step, like that also-obscure Hacking Education conference, toward the vision of learners providing input to occur in further iterations. _\"I wonder what small, but vital part we can play in that process, today\"_ indeed!", "postID": "z133c3zwmqj4fnhpd04cij3gnqnohjoix0w.1380728809322466"}

{"userName": "Brendan Storming", "sentiment_emotions": [], "hashtags": [], "userID": "105908654959068260105", "content": "&quot;Connection error&quot; does make for a powerful metaphor, especially when we&#39;re talking about connected learning and connectivism and making connections of various kinds, as the way to move beyond the factory model. There are really so many directions to go down with telling stories and analyzing variants of connection errors. One of the biggest ones is when people are having two different conversations, each talking about and focusing on things from a different schema, a different timeframe, different priorities, or simply with different motivations. The concept can be extended from errors, in the sense of deviation from an expected path, to examining bottlenecks and roadblocks and paths that have yet to be made. When people don&#39;t even have an expectation of connection, the lack of it isn&#39;t likely to read as an &quot;error,&quot; but as something not differentiable from the background of existence. The &quot;this is water&quot; video from a while back comes to mind as a way to look at that problem: THIS IS WATER David Foster Wallace [10m]", "sentiment_score": 0.041666666666666664, "cleanContent": "\"Connection error\" does make for a powerful metaphor, especially when we're talking about connected learning and connectivism and making connections of various kinds, as the way to move beyond the factory model. There are really so many directions to go down with telling stories and analyzing variants of connection errors. One of the biggest ones is when people are having two different conversations, each talking about and focusing on things from a different schema, a different timeframe, different priorities, or simply with different motivations. The concept can be extended from errors, in the sense of deviation from an expected path, to examining bottlenecks and roadblocks and paths that have yet to be made. When people don't even have an expectation of connection, the lack of it isn't likely to read as an \"error,\" but as something not differentiable from the background of existence. The \"this is water\" video from a while back comes to mind as a way to look at that problem: THIS IS WATER David Foster Wallace [10m]", "postID": "z13ottnxvpvtf5fyy04cij3gnqnohjoix0w.1380641178721466"}
{"userName": "Brendan Storming", "sentiment_emotions": [], "hashtags": [], "userID": "105908654959068260105", "content": "I&#39;m also reminded of this conflict that Brene Brown just wrote a blog post about. \u00a0In her various talks and books, she emphasizes connection, people&#39;s need for connection, and how shame breaks down connection. \u00a0Shame is likely in play when teachers are fretting over failing at their most basic tasks. \u00a0If it&#39;s a punishment from someone else, someone looking to make their lives more difficult, maybe all those struggles make more sense and are somehow easier to deal with? But, that&#39;s not the conflict at hand. \u00a0Brene explained in an interview how shame is present in every classroom. \u00a0A number of teachers, including BATs, got outraged and their feelings clear on Twitter and elsewhere. \u00a0In response, Brene wrote a blog post that clarifies her thoughts: http://brenebrown.com/2013/09/29/teachers-shame-worthiness-lesson-learned/ That&#39;s a whole conversation in itself, but it&#39;s also an example of a range of connection errors. \u00a0Arguably, the pain and punishment cycle is about shame. \u00a0And what happens, according to Brene Brown, is people numb themselves as a result. \u00a0And one of the best ways to numb is just not to pay attention to connections... not to look for them... not to miss them when they aren&#39;t there... and not to question them when they deserve an error message. All of this circles back to the question of metacognitive skills , the ones that are never discussed in many schools and classrooms. \u00a0How does one understand one&#39;s own mind, including thoughts, reactions, and ways of framing the world? Stepping back and engaging in metacognitive reflection, especially when it involves multiple people, is arguably what&#39;s needed to resolve a lot of connection errors that exist when people are chronically frustrated with their situations, or disengaged from them. But, if these aren&#39;t known skills, how can they be explained in ways that more people find worthwhile to explore and discuss? I think connection errors will be a useful term to add to those discussions. \u00a0Maybe a series of illustrations would help illustrate the points, and give people vocabulary and lenses to notice and discuss what&#39;s happening in different situations... even when &quot;there&#39;s no time&quot; for that.", "sentiment_score": 0.031618090452261306, "cleanContent": "I'm also reminded of this conflict that Brene Brown just wrote a blog post about. In her various talks and books, she emphasizes connection, people's need for connection, and how shame breaks down connection. Shame is likely in play when teachers are fretting over failing at their most basic tasks. If it's a punishment from someone else, someone looking to make their lives more difficult, maybe all those struggles make more sense and are somehow easier to deal with? But, that's not the conflict at hand. Brene explained in an interview how shame is present in every classroom. A number of teachers, including BATs, got outraged and their feelings clear on Twitter and elsewhere. In response, Brene wrote a blog post that clarifies her thoughts: That's a whole conversation in itself, but it's also an example of a range of connection errors. Arguably, the pain and punishment cycle is about shame. And what happens, according to Brene Brown, is people numb themselves as a result. And one of the best ways to numb is just not to pay attention to connections... not to look for them... not to miss them when they aren't there... and not to question them when they deserve an error message. All of this circles back to the question of metacognitive skills , the ones that are never discussed in many schools and classrooms. How does one understand one's own mind, including thoughts, reactions, and ways of framing the world? Stepping back and engaging in metacognitive reflection, especially when it involves multiple people, is arguably what's needed to resolve a lot of connection errors that exist when people are chronically frustrated with their situations, or disengaged from them. But, if these aren't known skills, how can they be explained in ways that more people find worthwhile to explore and discuss? I think connection errors will be a useful term to add to those discussions. Maybe a series of illustrations would help illustrate the points, and give people vocabulary and lenses to notice and discuss what's happening in different situations... even when \"there's no time\" for that.", "postID": "z13ottnxvpvtf5fyy04cij3gnqnohjoix0w.1380642222352466"}

(Oh, I can wipe off the table) Resiliency is a key skill that we need to teach the next generation as well as our own,as we sometimes aren&#39;t very good at it. We have our intention ...and then someone or some thing throws us a curve ball and a barrier to reaching our goal .....a bump in the road, on the choice of action, the path that we had taken. Resiliency means that we need to rethink and reassess the intention and how we are going to achieve it. So the powers gave you a new tool, ok...so now what? Do you challenge it or seek clarification? Do you seek guidance in meshing it with your current practices? Do you ignore it? Some choices will result in conflict and perhaps a redirection away from the intentions. Some choices will contribute to the greater community, fine-tuning the plan and your skills to be even better than before. And some choices will leave you floundering, spinning your wheels. Resiliency helps you get passed the initial emotional reaction and move into a conscious, proactive, empowering frame of mind - and towards effective solutions. Even though I ended up never using any of the math formulas from that class in my adult life, I was &quot;lucky&quot; that I did learn something &quot;useful&quot; from the maverick professor, who taught math as if it were a &quot;grand sweeping plan&quot; by God himself. I learned about Chaos Theory and Theory of Relativity, from a strange &quot;grand sweeping&quot; view that everything in nature and life itself, could be explained by math formulas that had more symbols than numbers in it. I guess the point I&#39;m making is, &quot;grand sweeping plans&quot; are all relative. A sand dune could be a &quot;grand (unsurmountable) hill&quot; to a Bedouin, or a small bump in the Sahara when seen from the sky, or a mere blob on the globe when looked at from a space shuttle, or a microscopic speck when looked at in relativity to the solar system. {"userName": "Mark Poole", "sentiment_emotions": [], "hashtags": [], "userID": "102169795540290746973", "content": "+ Justin Schwamm \u00a0 I&#39;m guessing the content of your blog post determines what ad shows up that day. This one showed up when I read your post today. http://goo.gl/PhLQ29 \u00a0 Grand sweeping plans are supposed to produce grand sweeping solutions. Our military often times come up with these types of plans. When it comes to war, the military uses descriptions like shock and awe as they describe how these plans will unroll. In the military the goal is to have soldiers follow the rules so that we can impose our desires on others. These grand sweeping plans are almost completely mechanized. People following rigid orders using machinery that does very specific tasks. This is similar to factory work. In the most recent TED talk by Ken Robinson he speaks on leadership in education. http://goo.gl/gy7cI3 . Robinson makes the point that because educating people is an organic process, leaders should move from a system of Command and Control \u00a0to one of Climate Control . \u00a0 http://goo.gl/Y2yGwt \u00a0 With this understanding, it is possible to let the powers play the role of general while at the community level one can protect the community from wounds caused when things break in the mechanized factory environment.", "sentiment_score": 0.07261904761904762, "cleanContent": "+ Justin Schwamm I'm guessing the content of your blog post determines what ad shows up that day. In the military the goal is to have soldiers follow the rules so that we can impose our desires on others. These grand sweeping plans are almost completely mechanized. People following rigid orders using machinery that does very specific tasks. This is similar to factory work. In the most recent TED talk by Ken Robinson he speaks on leadership in education. . Robinson makes the point that because educating people is an organic process, leaders should move from a system of Command and Control to one of Climate Control . With this understanding, it is possible to let the powers play the role of general while at the community level one can protect the community from wounds caused when things break in the mechanized factory environment.", "postID": "z13qxflbjtzzs3xr204cij3gnqnohjoix0w.1380030970216504"}
{"userName": "Ricardo Pietrobon", "sentiment_emotions": [], "hashtags": [], "userID": "106268032364497388036", "content": "Justin, interesting post. My take: Sweeping plans can be useful in terms of providing a general direction, but I believe that the key to execution are small experimental steps with a feedback that is as immediate as possible. That feedback will keep adjusting the course of action. That being said, obtaining constant feedback is not without its challenges. For one, immediate feedback in education will only go so far as the results of a given action sometimes can take many years to have an effect. It&#39;s just that one sentence mentioned by a teacher way back when that will stick with you for life. Second, constantly obtaining feedback significantly increases the workload. This is true for both quantitative and qualitative feedback. The key then is probably to have a feedback system that will cause the least friction and provide the best practical guidance, although to decide what that means is very difficult. Palma non sine pulvere PS: this is the first time I read your blog and I really like the reference to the Xs and Ys, but wonder how often they will recognize themselves.", "sentiment_score": 0.14009693877551022, "cleanContent": "Justin, interesting post. My take: Sweeping plans can be useful in terms of providing a general direction, but I believe that the key to execution are small experimental steps with a feedback that is as immediate as possible. That feedback will keep adjusting the course of action. That being said, obtaining constant feedback is not without its challenges. For one, immediate feedback in education will only go so far as the results of a given action sometimes can take many years to have an effect. It's just that one sentence mentioned by a teacher way back when that will stick with you for life. Second, constantly obtaining feedback significantly increases the workload. This is true for both quantitative and qualitative feedback. The key then is probably to have a feedback system that will cause the least friction and provide the best practical guidance, although to decide what that means is very difficult. {"userName": "Debbie Pribele", "sentiment_emotions": [], "hashtags": [], "userID": "113508712170563926845", "content": "Equilibrium, in my opinion, is the basis of addictions. Our bodies and minds get used to what is &quot;normal&quot; at the moment and change the &quot;normal&quot; in any way and the body/mind is out of whack and some of us or in some situation, we &quot;crave&quot; that old way, needing it to put things back &quot;in sync&quot;.\u00a0 This can be removal of alcohol from the system or anxiety or fear. Let&#39;s say a person is used to being yelled at (or doing the yelling). The body does some chemical thingy during the yelling episode. When the yelling takes place frequently enough the chemical--reaction-thingy becomes the norm and the body gets used to whatever is happening. Take away the yelling, reduce the chemical-reaction-thingy and the system, the chemicals, are out of balance. We, then, either have to bring the yelling back, to put things back in balance, or we have to let the body get used to the new normal, the new balance, the one without the chemical-reaction to yelling.\u00a0 So yah, change is challenging. ... unless you know what is happening, believe in the change and have the ability to make the change.", "sentiment_score": 0.05189732142857143, "cleanContent": "Equilibrium, in my opinion, is the basis of addictions. {"userName": "Brendan Storming", "sentiment_emotions": [], "hashtags": [], "userID": "105908654959068260105", "content": "+ Roz Hussin \u00a0Exactly... professional identity is a core part of the issue. \u00a0How can educators be invited to update their schemas? I think part of the answer is in helping the students update theirs as well. \u00a0One clip in + Michael Wesch &#39;s Visions of Students Today features a community college instructor saying, &quot;The teachers are not the ones pushing the same old idea of things... it&#39;s that the students are as well. \u00a0They want to know what they need to do to get the grade.&quot; -- just after a segment from a student about being &quot;a barcode with a number assigned.&quot; &quot;The Visions of Students Today&quot; 2011 Remix One (trailer) [3m] Michael Wesch also digs further into that point about the questions students ask in his talk,\u00a0 TEDxKC - Michael Wesch - From Knowledgeable to Knowledge-Able [18m] So, what&#39;s to be done? \u00a0Some students and some teachers are trying to push the boundaries of things, but the subject-based, age-graded, letter-grade-assessment format of school keeps things in place. \u00a0And, many teachers don&#39;t have time to learn new tech skills, let alone new paradigms of learning and teaching. Meanwhile, standardized test-based accountability provides an additional pressure on many teachers and schools. \u00a0And, from a corporate-reform efficiency perspective, why have every teacher spending so much time photocopying identical packets? \u00a0It&#39;s this what books are for, printed on gigantic presses that can churn out millions of copies? Then again, some argue that the textbook is obsolete: &quot;The Pain Test 1: Inverting the Textbook,&quot; http://tcedstartup101.wordpress.com/2012/09/22/the-pain-test-1-inverting-the-textbook/ &quot;...young learners, who grew up in this rapidly changing world and know that obsolete information is being \u201cdelivered\u201d to them, are highly skeptical of slick, pre-packaged information. \u00a0The more pre-packaged it feels \u2013 and the more \u201cflat and dead\u201d it seems to the learner \u2013 the less willing they are to entertain it.&quot; And yet that contrasts with + Justin Schwamm &#39;s contrasting observation of students wanting to just be handed a packet or just be told what to do , and the common questions like, &quot;what do I need to do to get the grade?&quot; It seems to me that the focus on points and grades is emphasized in K-12 education, in large part because of the importance of college. \u00a0But at the college level, it seems that many faculty find this obsession with grades and points a distraction from &quot;real learning,&quot; and struggle to find a way to un-do the zombification (or at least cope with the reality they have to deal with.) \u00a0 And yet, the college structure itself is structured around grades and credits at the institutional and credentialing level. So, it all circles back to intention , the point + Debbie Pribele \u00a0regularly brings up. \u00a0What are people&#39;s intentions, not only in terms of a specific assignment or lesson (which is important), but in terms of the overall journey of education?", "sentiment_score": 0.07238051470588236, "cleanContent": "+ Roz Hussin Exactly... professional identity is a core part of the issue. And yet, the college structure itself is structured around grades and credits at the institutional and credentialing level. {"userName": "Justin Schwamm", "sentiment_emotions": [], "hashtags": [], "userID": "102340336817210055995", "content": "+ Brendan Storming \u00a0- My goodness, what a wonderful conversation to come home to after a L-O-N-G day! \u00a0A long, good day, as it turns out, partly thanks to an amazing set of realizations this week. \u00a0I took another look at &quot;the thirteen&quot; in that upper-level class of mine, thought about their preferred learning modes, and realized that \u2013 like you and + Roz Hussin \u00a0among many other folks I know \u2013 most of them are visual-kinesthetic learners. \u00a0One simple little graphic organizer to help them see and physically move vocabulary around, and they were delighted; one amazing strategy that + Emily Lewis \u00a0suggested, and I think they&#39;ll find reading Latin a lot more pleasurable. \u00a0We&#39;ll be putting phrases onto cards and physically moving the cards around to show time relationships between them on Monday, and if that works, it will become a constantly-available option for them. \u00a0I think it will work because (1) it will help them focus on just a few words at a time rather than a wall of text and (2) by physically moving the words around, they&#39;ll be able to engage their kinesthetic mode, which is strong-strong-strong for all of them. A long, good day, as it turns out, partly thanks to an amazing set of realizations this week. I took another look at \"the thirteen\" in that upper-level class of mine, thought about their preferred learning modes, and realized that \u2013 like you and + Roz Hussin among many other folks I know \u2013 most of them are visual-kinesthetic learners. One simple little graphic organizer to help them see and physically move vocabulary around, and they were delighted; one amazing strategy that + Emily Lewis suggested, and I think they'll find reading Latin a lot more pleasurable. We'll be putting phrases onto cards and physically moving the cards around to show time relationships between them on Monday, and if that works, it will become a constantly-available option for them. I think it will work because (1) it will help them focus on just a few words at a time rather than a wall of text and (2) by physically moving the words around, they'll be able to engage their kinesthetic mode, which is strong-strong-strong for all of them. In a \"perfect\" world, I suppose I would have realized this a year ago and saved all of us a LOT of trouble. I had two remarkable illustrations of that today alone. First, during the smaller Latin I class, we were talking about teachers and tests ... and about teachers who give tests but take forever to grade them . {"userName": "Debbie Pribele", "sentiment_emotions": [], "hashtags": [], "userID": "113508712170563926845", "content": "my awakening to the &quot;with&quot; not &quot;for&quot; came after my husband died. I know that I&#39;ve told this story before. After he died, I was quite active in the suicide support groups and, oh, the panic I would feel as I strived to &quot;save&quot; people. Then one day a person was definitely on the edge, so to speak, and nothing I said changed his/her mind. It was a horrible feeling and then I realized that my role was to hold out my hand. It was the other person&#39;s decision whether or not to grab hold of the hand and use it as support through the troubled times.\u00a0 This was his/her journey, not mine; this was his/her lesson to work through, baggage to toss aside, not mine.\u00a0 In later years, as I worked in the mental health field, I took that Wisdom and applied it to clients. If I fixed their problems, eliminated their stressors, I was also eliminating or diminishing their learning curve, their skill-development, their self-worth, their journey, their personal growth.\u00a0 &quot;With&quot;, not &quot;for&quot;. I like that. It makes it SO easy to understand and remember.", "sentiment_score": 0.07134703196347032, "cleanContent": "my awakening to the \"with\" not \"for\" came after my husband died. I know that I've told this story before. After he died, I was quite active in the suicide support groups and, oh, the panic I would feel as I strived to \"save\" people. Then one day a person was definitely on the edge, so to speak, and nothing I said changed his/her mind. It was a horrible feeling and then I realized that my role was to hold out my hand. It was the other person's decision whether or not to grab hold of the hand and use it as support through the troubled times. This was his/her journey, not mine; this was his/her lesson to work through, baggage to toss aside, not mine. In later years, as I worked in the mental health field, I took that Wisdom and applied it to clients. If I fixed their problems, eliminated their stressors, I was also eliminating or diminishing their learning curve, their skill-development, their self-worth, their journey, their personal growth. \"With\", not \"for\". {"userName": "Debbie Pribele", "sentiment_emotions": [], "hashtags": [], "userID": "113508712170563926845", "content": "I&#39;ll share another early childhood story that I&#39;ve probably shared before &gt;&gt; I had a little guy who wouldn&#39;t participate in group activities. I tried all the tricky coercion techniques with no change in behaviour.\u00a0 Then I started group activities with the song, &quot;This is what I can do; see if you can do it too&quot;. When it came to his turn he would just sit there, looking a little fearful. But rather than moving on or putting pressure on him, I used the &quot;sitting still&quot; as his contribution and we call copied the pose.\u00a0 He then, on the following day, shook his head &quot;no&quot; ( determined not to participate); and so I included the head shake in the song. At first he was not impressed but, the next day, \u00a0he had a slight grin. And we copied that. After that, he made deliberate movements and the fears were gone. What were the helpful factors? Keeping it safe; no judgements; no &quot;wrong&quot; answers; joyful community sharing his journey without teasing/laughter/judging. .. and starting small. I don&#39;t know how this translates into high school but there might be something in there worth contemplating.", "sentiment_score": -0.03209459459459459, "cleanContent": "I'll share another early childhood story that I've probably shared before >> I had a little guy who wouldn't participate in group activities. I tried all the tricky coercion techniques with no change in behaviour. Then I started group activities with the song, \"This is what I can do; see if you can do it too\". When it came to his turn he would just sit there, looking a little fearful. But rather than moving on or putting pressure on him, I used the \"sitting still\" as his contribution and we call copied the pose. He then, on the following day, shook his head \"no\" ( determined not to participate); and so I included the head shake in the song. At first he was not impressed but, the next day, he had a slight grin. And we copied that. After that, he made deliberate movements and the fears were gone. What were the helpful factors? Keeping it safe; no judgements; no \"wrong\" answers; joyful community sharing his journey without teasing/laughter/judging. .. and starting small. I don't know how this translates into high school but there might be something in there worth contemplating.", "postID": "z13ezr3owoecj1t3r23nsv4xox3fx3rcb.1378853250497082"}

{"userName": "Mark Poole", "sentiment_emotions": [], "hashtags": [], "userID": "102169795540290746973", "content": "+ don arnoldy \u00a0wrote Their egos are fragile, and they are risk-averse. They don&#39;t fail until you say they fail. Its safer to take a 0 &quot;cause I didn&#39;t turn it in,&quot; than it is to turn it in and have you judge them unworthy. I\u2019m not so sure kids live down to a label placed on them as + Justin Schwamm \u00a0wrote or they are risk averse. From the No Man is an Island \u00a0prologue. Our life , as individual persons and as members of a perplexed and struggling race, provokes us with the evidence that it must have meaning, and live according to it. We have, therefore, something to live for. The process of living, of growing up, and becoming a person, is precisely the gradually increasing awareness of what that something is. This is a difficult task, for many reasons. When a kid takes a zero instead of trying to do an assignment this is their way of fighting back. Them taking a zero is a mirror image of a teacher threatening and then giving a zero. Partial credit has not helped them figure out who they are so far and an A \u00a0or 100 is not going to happen. A zero is the clear best choice when you are a cognitive refugee.\u00a0 The example + Debbie Pribele \u00a0 wrote about where the young boy refused to take part in the circle singing activity shows what happens when those in charge demonstrate that the kid matters. The constant drum beat of grades matter most, says to many kids, grades are more important than them as individuals. Our life provokes us with the evidence that it must have meaning. School for many is the opposite of evidence that life has meaning. Years of being told what to do for a significant part of a 24 hour day steals time from the process of figuring out who we are. By the time a junior or senior year rolls around, a significant number of kids who have not already dropped out, are ready to figure out who they are and taking a zero is the fastest way to do this.\u00a0 The No Man is an Island prologue is full of understanding for why we see kids behaving as they do in school and at home. http://goo.gl/MrnfZW", "sentiment_score": 0.02242962962962963, "cleanContent": "+ don arnoldy wrote Their egos are fragile, and they are risk-averse. {"userName": "Justin Schwamm", "sentiment_emotions": [], "hashtags": [], "userID": "102340336817210055995", "content": "+ Mike Trainum \u00a0- There&#39;s still time, of course ... maybe not for the class , but for the Tres Columnae Project stories. \u00a0I can send you some of the supporting materials if you&#39;d like. + Brendan Storming \u00a0 + Roz Hussin \u00a0- I think that the &quot;TC&quot; stories may be more important for CoRe learners than I had realized ... and I knew they were important! \u00a0By presenting characters who are very much like us in many ways, but very far separated from us in space and time, they allow for conversations that are-but-aren&#39;t about us ... and that leads to a safe space for deeper conversations when the time is right. \u00a0I spent a long time trying to use textbook-based stories and characters for that purpose, and half-succeeding ... but it&#39;s a lot easier when the materials are designed for the purpose rather than repurposed. We&#39;ll be looking at driving and restraining forces for the next few months, and eventually everyone should be able \u2013 and possibly even willing \u2013 to see the ones at work in their own lives. \u00a0D, C, D, and E were working very hard to avoid both the story and the diagram today, which (as I&#39;ve discovered over the time I&#39;ve known them) usually means that they&#39;re half-hoping-half-fearing that it&#39;s really significant and personal for them. I can send you some of the supporting materials if you'd like. + Brendan Storming + Roz Hussin - I think that the \"TC\" stories may be more important for CoRe learners than I had realized ... and I knew they were important! By presenting characters who are very much like us in many ways, but very far separated from us in space and time, they allow for conversations that are-but-aren't about us ... and that leads to a safe space for deeper conversations when the time is right. I spent a long time trying to use textbook-based stories and characters for that purpose, and half-succeeding ... but it's a lot easier when the materials are designed for the purpose rather than repurposed. We'll be looking at driving and restraining forces for the next few months, and eventually everyone should be able \u2013 and possibly even willing \u2013 to see the ones at work in their own lives. D, C, D, and E were working very hard to avoid both the story and the diagram today, which (as I've discovered over the time I've known them) usually means that they're half-hoping-half-fearing that it's really significant and personal for them. {"userName": "Niti Beri", "sentiment_emotions": [], "hashtags": [], "userID": "102647381858824443280", "content": "Re-Think Your PhD. The pursuit of a PhD is a noble venture. You spend years and years of your life toiling away to move human knowledge in a small tiny area forward. Ideally there is a rich reward at the end of it, or at least a fulfilling career that pays well enough. A lot of PhDs at the end of their education/thesis would move on to a position in academia to teach / pursue knowledge further. The graph below illustrates the sad truth.\u00a0 Since 1982, almost 800,000 PhDs were awarded in science and engineering (S&amp;E) fields, whereas only about 100,000 academic faculty positions were created in those fields within the same time frame. The number of S&amp;E PhDs awarded annually has also increased over this time frame, from ~19,000 in 1982 to ~36,000 in 2011. The number of faculty positions created each year, however, has not changed, with roughly 3,000 new positions created annually. Source:\u00a0 http://goo.gl/Yl0g1y So if you are going to get a PhD, consider non-academic options for your post-doc career. The challenge, and it really is a big challenge, is to ask oneself if non-academic jobs in your field need or benefit from a PhD. \u00a0If it does not, all your investment in earning the PhD might not have a commensurate financial impact on your life (or even bring professional satisfaction). This last part does make me a little sad. We need a percentage of humans to keep pushing the boundaries of knowledge and propel us forward. But this graph, and the subsequent realities, seem to be working against that pursuit.\u00a0 Do you have an answer to this dilemma?", "replyCount": 0, "cleanContent": "Re-Think Your PhD. The pursuit of a PhD is a noble venture. You spend years and years of your life toiling away to move human knowledge in a small tiny area forward. Ideally there is a rich reward at the end of it, or at least a fulfilling career that pays well enough. A lot of PhDs at the end of their education/thesis would move on to a position in academia to teach / pursue knowledge further. The graph below illustrates the sad truth. Since 1982, almost 800,000 PhDs were awarded in science and engineering (S&E) fields, whereas only about 100,000 academic faculty positions were created in those fields within the same time frame. The number of S&E PhDs awarded annually has also increased over this time frame, from ~19,000 in 1982 to ~36,000 in 2011. The number of faculty positions created each year, however, has not changed, with roughly 3,000 new positions created annually. Source: So if you are going to get a PhD, consider non-academic options for your post-doc career. The challenge, and it really is a big challenge, is to ask oneself if non-academic jobs in your field need or benefit from a PhD. If it does not, all your investment in earning the PhD might not have a commensurate financial impact on your life (or even bring professional satisfaction). This last part does make me a little sad. We need a percentage of humans to keep pushing the boundaries of knowledge and propel us forward. But this graph, and the subsequent realities, seem to be working against that pursuit. Do you have an answer to this dilemma?", "sentiment_score": 0.05061744966442953, "postID": "z13dw1bhkzzhztsiz04cg5pzswq4gfw55fw"}

{"userName": "Niti Beri", "sentiment_emotions": [], "hashtags": ["#moviereviewsindia", "#thelunchbox"], "userID": "102647381858824443280", "content": "#moviereviewsindia \u00a0 #thelunchbox \u00a0 Review: The Lunch Box - You Will Savour This One Rating: 4.5/5 Ritesh Batra&#39;s The Lunchbox is a movie about a love that blossoms by accident - it all begins when the Mumbai Dubbawalas mistakenly deliver the Lunch Box prepared by Ila (played by Nimrat Kaur) to Mr. Fernandez (played by Irfan Khan). But, this movie is not just about the love between the placid widower and the forlorn housewife; \u00a0it is also a movie about relationships that our day to day life gifts us with - those beautiful bonds that cannot be named but add substance to our life - the neighborhood &#39;aunty&quot;, the office colleague, the cigarette buddy or the morning train companion, we all have these people around us, enriching our lives in ways we might not even notice. Mr. Fenandez&#39; lunch box and the movie are both full of delectable desi flavors -while the &quot;next-door Aunty&quot; flavor \u00a0is the best of them all, it is the &quot;Mumbai daily life&quot; tarka that completes the recipe. The brilliance of Irfan Khan and Nawazuddin \u00a0Siddiqui put together is the best thing that can happen to a debutant director. \u00a0Playing the character of a reticent man meant that the feelings of the character had to be depicted more though expressions than dialogues - no one except Irfan could have done justice to this character - each emotion and each thought had been expressed so well that it turned the movie into a masterpiece. Nawaz and Nimrat too have delivered a phenomenal performance. Nimrat beautifully depicts the agony and loneliness of all those housewives who spend their lives playing the role of a dutiful wife and mother with near perfection while their souls crave for that little bit of time and attention from their husbands. The screenplay is all about attention to detail; this makes a few scenes in the movie too slow for an impatient viewer - especially the first lunch time scene where Infan&#39;s character spends a lot of time looking at and smelling the food before taking the first bite.The cinematography that ensures that the audience experience hunger pangs every time the lunch box is opened is worthy of a mention too. This Lunch Box truly deserves a place is Bollywood&#39;s treasure box.", "replyCount": 2, "cleanContent": "#moviereviewsindia #thelunchbox Review: The Lunch Box - You Will Savour This One Rating: 4.5/5 Ritesh Batra's The Lunchbox is a movie about a love that blossoms by accident - it all begins when the Mumbai Dubbawalas mistakenly deliver the Lunch Box prepared by Ila (played by Nimrat Kaur) to Mr. Fernandez (played by Irfan Khan). But, this movie is not just about the love between the placid widower and the forlorn housewife; it is also a movie about relationships that our day to day life gifts us with - those beautiful bonds that cannot be named but add substance to our life - the neighborhood 'aunty\", the office colleague, the cigarette buddy or the morning train companion, we all have these people around us, enriching our lives in ways we might not even notice. Mr. Fenandez' lunch box and the movie are both full of delectable desi flavors -while the \"next-door Aunty\" flavor is the best of them all, it is the \"Mumbai daily life\" tarka that completes the recipe. The brilliance of Irfan Khan and Nawazuddin Siddiqui put together is the best thing that can happen to a debutant director. Playing the character of a reticent man meant that the feelings of the character had to be depicted more though expressions than dialogues - no one except Irfan could have done justice to this character - each emotion and each thought had been expressed so well that it turned the movie into a masterpiece. Nawaz and Nimrat too have delivered a phenomenal performance. Nimrat beautifully depicts the agony and loneliness of all those housewives who spend their lives playing the role of a dutiful wife and mother with near perfection while their souls crave for that little bit of time and attention from their husbands. The screenplay is all about attention to detail; this makes a few scenes in the movie too slow for an impatient viewer - especially the first lunch time scene where Infan's character spends a lot of time looking at and smelling the food before taking the first bite.The cinematography that ensures that the audience experience hunger pangs every time the lunch box is opened is worthy of a mention too. This Lunch Box truly deserves a place is Bollywood's treasure box.", "sentiment_score": 0.15339999999999998, "postID": "z13kfnkgtnegxlqa004cg5pzswq4gfw55fw"}

{"userName": "Movie Models", "sentiment_emotions": ["joy"], "hashtags": [], "userID": "103305044081987821590", "content": "I primed the parts with grey primer, then marked out my lines with pencil and sometimes masking tape. I then used a sharp rat tailed file to make a pilot for the drill, then pre-drilled each line, (only drilling about half way through) then went back and did a final drill through. This gave me the option to &quot;nudge&quot; a window slightly if needed, and kept the drill from melting the plastic. Any windows that are out of line will be blocked off. I&#39;m going to put canopy glue in them and can then black out a few where needed. They wouldn&#39;t all be lit at once anyway.
